sunny breezy- 55F- blue gill- bass or two
Sunny- 78 F.  Light breeze.  1 Canada goose.  1 mallard family.
Partly cloudy- hazy.  80 F.  Bluegill.  Channel level very low.
Mostly sunny- 75 F.  Light breeze.  Floating grass island (turf from lake bottom) covered with turtles.
temp 74 degrees- mostly sunny- few clouds- light breeze

column1: 'floating' grass island near permanent island had a dozen small sun turtles
permanent island had dozens of snails on shoreline
5 geese  have a home on northeast shore of Beauleau Lake

column2: temps in the upper 70s- mostly cloudy with peeks of sun- light breeze

column1: water level starting to recede:  channel depth is only 2 feet at Beauleau entrance-

column2: temps in the upper 70s- full sun- light breeze

column1: bluegill swimming in schools near channel entrance
duck family on lake - mom and 6 ducklings

column2: temp 82 degrees- full sun- strong breeze
temp 83 degrees- full sun- no wind
63 degrees- sunny- light breeze- some ducks
70 degrees- cloudy with peeks of sun- light wind

column1: channel from Koonz too narrow for pontoons- too shallow for trolling motors

column2: 64 degrees- sun mixed with clouds- light breeze

column1: small mats of grass from bottom floating on surface

column2: 74 degrees- mostly sunny- few clouds- calm

column1: grss mats from bottom floating on surface- small turtles sunning themselves on them- 2 ducks in channel to Koonz Lake- heron flew overhead

column2: Sun/clouds mix- 85 degrees- light breeze.  Lake is at lowest spring level we have ever experienced.  Channel nearly unnavigable on Beauliue side. Goose family moves back and forth from Koonz Lake to Beaulieu Lake.  Snails are huge this year.
Sunny- breezy- 78 degrees.  Goose family was in the channel - 2 adults- 10 young.  We have gotten 6-7 inches of rain during June.

78 degrees- sun- slight breeze.  Some clumps of blue-green algae floating in middle of lake.  Maders report snapping turtles and otter frequenting their swimming area.  Channel is now 2 1/2 feet deep in middle.  We have had our wettest July on record - 7 1/2".
68 degrees- sunny- calm.  Stopped out at island.  Saw 5 turtles- one blue heron on island.  We continued to get above record rainfall during month of August.
70 degrees; mostly sunny; light breeze.  Above average precipitation for year has caused lake levels to recover.  Channel is 3 ft. deep and navigable.  Small bluegill and bass in channel.
80 degrees; sunny; light breeze.  Lake received almost 7" of rain during week of June 20- 2011 thru June 24- 2011- so lake level continues to recover.
75 degrees; sunny; light breeze.  Many clumps of soft-ball sized blue-green algae floating around island.  Yuck!
78 degrees; sunny; light breeze.  6 geese on northwest shore.
Sunny- 86 degrees- light breeze - 13 geese- 2 adult and 11 young- family of 5 ducks
Sun with some clouds- 80 degrees- light north wind
Sunny- some clouds- 70 degrees- calm - small bass
Sunny- some hazy clouds- 78 degrees- no breeze
Cloudy- 60 degrees- windy- feels like fall
Sunny- some hazy clouds- 68 degrees- breezy.  A very tall heron strolling along shore to west of channel.  He took off and landed several times - so graceful.
80 degrees- sun- light breeze.  Pair of loons.
80 degrees- sunny- breezy.  Loon diving out in the middle.
74 degrees- partly sunny- calm.  Lake has several large clumps of blue-green algae along north end of lake.

80 degrees- partly cloudy- calm.  Water levels highest we've seen in 18 years.  Island ground appears to be underwater.  Birch trees dying all around the shoreline.  Family of 12 geese in east corner near boat landing.  1 loon enjoying himself out in the middle of the lake.
74 degrees- overcast chrome-colored sky- rain impending- gusty breeze.
74 degrees- partly cloudy- light breeze.  Many- many clumps of blue-green algae along north shoreline to left of channel as you look to the north.
Partly cloudy- breezy- water level highest we have observed in 20 years.  Spotted a pair of loons- a couple of turtles- and a blue heron.  Lots of regular algae.
72 degrees- full sun- light breeze.  Lake levels still very high.  Spotted a loon family of 3:  mom- dad- and baby loon!
85 degrees- mostly sunny- breezy.  Lake levels still at highest level in recent years.
88 degrees- mostly sunny- breezy- water level high- one loon on nest on island- pair of cranes flying overhead
85 degrees- partly cloudy- windy.  Pair of loons popped up beside my paddle board- communicating by tapping their beaks on surface of the water.
75 degrees- sunny- light breeze.  Pair of loons swimming in middle.  Lots of small bass along shoreline.
72 degrees- cloudy- breezy.  Turtles sunning themselves along shoreline.  Large northern swimming along shore opposite of the island.  Many large clumps of blue-green algae all over the lake :(

85 degrees- full sun- very light breeze. Lake is at highest level we have seen in 21 years.  Island is now underwater.  Had to raise our dock twice this summer already.  Water is very dark brown in color. Newer species of small- oval shaped lily pads have taken over many parts of the shoreline.  Mother loon and one chick were enjoying the warm day.  Lots of turtles sunning themselves along the shoreline.

85 degrees- mostly sunny- some hazy clouds.  Water still at highest level in 21 years.  Water color is darker brown than we remember from the past.  It looks murky towards the bottom of the water column as the bottom sediment seems churned up.
82 degrees- mostly sunny- light breeze.  Water level continues to rise.  Loon mother teaching loon chick to dive.  Funny watching him pop back up like a bobber :)

77 degrees- hazy sunshine- light breeze.  Water color very dark brown and bottom sediment is churned up.  Mother loon continues diving lessons with baby and feeds him small fish.  They call to each other when separated.  Island on Beaulieu is 2 feet underwater.  Cove to the ease of the island is deep enough to take paddle board in  a ways to explore; can get in about 60 feet or so.  Lake levels continue to rise weekly.

72 degrees- partly sunny- light breeze.  Water level continues to rise weekly due to unprecedented rainfall.  Channel getting wider; point on Beauleau east side of channel partly underwater.  By October 10- the point was completely underwater.  Water color still very dark brown and sediment on bottom churned up.  Mother loon trying to give baby flying lessons.  Comical to watch :)

82 degrees- partly sunny- light breeze- impending storms.  Both lakes brown- churned up from all of the recent rain.  Lakes at highest level we have seen in 22 years of staying here.  No shorelines anywhere- trees standing in water all long shore- channel between Beaulieu and Koonz lakes no longer defined.  Island on Beaulieu has completely disappeared underwater.  Also heard from full-time residents that there was a major fish die-off over the past winter due to severe decrease in water oxygen levels.  Noticed very few fish during outing - mostly small schools of minnows- a couple of bluegill- one crappie.  Several turtles were sunning themselves on partially submerged fallen trees.  Did not see loons.

87 degrees- hazy sun- light breeze.  Water brown and very churned up.  Pair of loons swimming/diving.  Heard from full-time residents that their two eggs were destroyed by predators :(  Lake remains at highest level we have seen.
80 degrees- partly sunny- light breeze.  Water still churned up and murky but improvement over last observance.  One loon.
76 degrees- mostly sunny- slight breeze.  Lake level down slightly- inch or two.  Pair of loons swimming in channel.
72 degrees- sunny- some gusty breeze.  Water level down again slightly.  Saw a few turtles on shoreline- a couple of small schools of very small fish.

66 degrees- smoky hazy sun (due to smoke from wild fires in the west drifting over the state)- strong breeze.  Saw half a dozen turtles sunning themselves on shore.  1 heron in newly-formed north cove- west side of channel.  Lake level down again- possibly 8" from highest point in spring.
